WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.880
Without further ado, I'll hand over the stage to Tyler Morgan-Wall.

00:00:10.880 --> 00:00:13.000
Thank you, Mara.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:14.760
Hi, everyone.

00:00:14.760 --> 00:00:18.360
Thank you for coming, and thank you, RStudio, for inviting me to talk.

00:00:18.360 --> 00:00:19.879
My name is Tyler Morgan-Wall.

00:00:19.879 --> 00:00:22.400
I'm the developer of the rayshader package.

00:00:22.400 --> 00:00:27.020
I'm a researcher at IDA in Washington, D.C., and today, I'm going to be talking to you

00:00:27.020 --> 00:00:32.779
about 3D ggplots with rayshader.

00:00:32.779 --> 00:00:36.619
So first things first, what do I hope you get out of this talk?

00:00:36.619 --> 00:00:41.740
20 minutes from now, I guarantee that each and every one of you will know how to create

00:00:41.740 --> 00:00:46.700
beautiful 3D ggplots in just a few lines of code.

00:00:46.700 --> 00:00:52.180
I also guarantee that this specific capability is so straightforward that you won't have

00:00:52.180 --> 00:00:56.340
to look up any additional documentation to get started, even though rayshader has a great

00:00:56.340 --> 00:01:03.299
package and website at rayshader.com with extensive documentation and examples.

00:01:03.299 --> 00:01:08.180
And finally, I guarantee that by the end of this talk, you'll be thinking to yourself,

00:01:08.180 --> 00:01:12.339
wow, that guy really loves spinning 3D plots.

00:01:12.339 --> 00:01:14.699
I do.

00:01:14.699 --> 00:01:16.980
So what is rayshader?

00:01:16.980 --> 00:01:21.860
I could start first by describing it in words like a normal person, but luckily, this year,

00:01:21.860 --> 00:01:23.779
I don't have to.

00:01:23.779 --> 00:01:28.580
Because I have a great visual aid created by the unparalleled RStudio artist in residence,

00:01:28.580 --> 00:01:31.220
Allison Horst.

00:01:31.220 --> 00:01:35.839
Rayshader is a package designed to create 2D and 3D visualizations in R, specializing

00:01:35.839 --> 00:01:36.839
in maps.

00:01:36.839 --> 00:01:42.480
It includes a wide variety of functions, here represented by fuzzy functional monsters that

00:01:42.480 --> 00:01:47.580
help you build, color, and annotate and beautify your visualizations.

00:01:47.580 --> 00:01:53.120
Specifically, rayshader uses a technique called raytracing in order to realistically simulate

00:01:53.459 --> 00:01:56.599
how light falls on 3D models and landscapes.

00:01:56.599 --> 00:02:02.199
On the left, you can see how rayshader calculates the shadows cast by buildings in Philadelphia

00:02:02.199 --> 00:02:07.180
using a combination of LiDAR data and the suncalc package to calculate the position

00:02:07.180 --> 00:02:09.880
of the sun in the sky.

00:02:09.880 --> 00:02:14.679
Rayshader can take these 2D maps and then project them into 3D, as we see here on the

00:02:14.679 --> 00:02:16.720
right.

00:02:16.720 --> 00:02:20.979
So rayshader also includes functions that you can apply post-processing effects to enhance

00:02:20.979 --> 00:02:22.399
these 3D maps.

00:02:22.399 --> 00:02:26.960
Here I've added a depth of field effect to blur areas away from the focal point, as well

00:02:26.960 --> 00:02:31.119
as a camera vignetting effect to add a subtle darkening around the edges like you'd see

00:02:31.119 --> 00:02:33.199
in a DSLR.

00:02:33.199 --> 00:02:40.800
This 3D visualization was created entirely in R with no external software required.

00:02:40.800 --> 00:02:45.320
Rayshader does all this with a straightforward pipeable interface where you use elevation

00:02:45.320 --> 00:02:48.520
data to generate shadows and maps.

00:02:48.520 --> 00:02:54.320
Here the Hobart object at the top of the chain is simply a 2D array of elevation values

00:02:54.320 --> 00:02:55.360
at every point.

00:02:55.360 --> 00:02:57.440
It's just an R matrix.

00:02:57.440 --> 00:03:02.539
We use that first to generate a color layer, add a water layer, add some shadow layers,

00:03:02.539 --> 00:03:04.779
and then finally plot the map.

00:03:04.779 --> 00:03:10.880
To project this map into 3D, we simply replace the plot map function with the plot 3D function

00:03:10.880 --> 00:03:14.119
and include the original matrix of height values.

00:03:14.119 --> 00:03:19.039
This function generates a 3D mesh generated by the Hobart matrix and then paints the surface

00:03:19.039 --> 00:03:24.020
of it with the output of everything above.

00:03:24.020 --> 00:03:28.360
If you want to learn more about all the great mapping and 3D printing features in Rayshader,

00:03:28.360 --> 00:03:31.759
I encourage you to watch my RStudio conference talk from last year.

00:03:31.759 --> 00:03:35.880
Additionally, if you want a more extensive introduction, I have a freely available master

00:03:35.880 --> 00:03:39.699
class I taught along with the MUSE program at the University of Pennsylvania that walks

00:03:39.699 --> 00:03:42.000
you through several comprehensive examples.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:44.199
There's video available of that as well.

00:03:44.199 --> 00:03:48.919
Check out my GitHub page to learn more.

00:03:48.919 --> 00:03:53.960
Mapping is great, but one thing I always get when I demo Rayshader is people say, I'd love

00:03:53.960 --> 00:03:58.479
to have a reason to use that, but I don't work with geographic data.

00:03:58.479 --> 00:04:03.399
So let's say I wanted to extend Rayshader to work with other types of data.

00:04:03.399 --> 00:04:08.919
Let's first specify what type of 3D plot we want to work on.

00:04:08.919 --> 00:04:13.399
Typically when we talk about 3D plots, there are four common types we're referring to.

00:04:13.399 --> 00:04:18.000
First is the 3D scatter plot, which is a bunch of points floating in space.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:24.040
Second is the 3D line plot, which is a bunch of points floating in space connected by lines.

00:04:24.040 --> 00:04:30.040
Third is the surface plot, which is a contiguous mesh of points representing a solid surface.

00:04:30.040 --> 00:04:37.760
And finally is the abomination, which is what happens when you take a plot that doesn't

00:04:37.839 --> 00:04:42.640
want to be 3D, but you pull it into the third dimension anyway.

00:04:42.640 --> 00:04:46.440
To make sure we don't make any abominations, we'll only use 3D plots when we have three

00:04:46.440 --> 00:04:52.320
continuous variables, variables we map to the X, Y, and Z directions.

00:04:52.320 --> 00:04:56.760
We'll also avoid plots that involve data floating in space, as those suffer from the inability

00:04:56.760 --> 00:05:00.839
of the reader to correctly determine the depth of the points in space, leading to ambiguities

00:05:00.839 --> 00:05:03.000
in interpreting the data.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:06.920
Surface plots suffer far less from this problem, since the regular grid gives the reader more

00:05:06.920 --> 00:05:11.160
perceptual cues to the data's spatial ordering.

00:05:11.160 --> 00:05:15.880
We will also remove the axes, which might seem heretical in data viz, but axes in 3D

00:05:15.880 --> 00:05:18.399
don't work the same way they do in 2D.

00:05:18.399 --> 00:05:22.720
The viewer can't unambiguously map the data back to their values.

00:05:22.720 --> 00:05:28.399
Putting your 3D visualization in a box rarely improves it, and if a visualization requires

00:05:28.399 --> 00:05:35.239
the axes to be interpretable, it's likely not a good candidate for 3D in the first place.

00:05:35.239 --> 00:05:37.359
So we're going to focus on surface plots.

00:05:37.359 --> 00:05:39.619
What's our interface going to look like?

00:05:39.619 --> 00:05:43.440
When you're creating a new software package, one good idea before you start is to survey

00:05:43.440 --> 00:05:45.359
what tools are already out there.

00:05:45.359 --> 00:05:46.359
This serves two purposes.

00:05:46.359 --> 00:05:50.519
One, to figure out whether you even need to write your package, whether the niche is already

00:05:50.519 --> 00:05:51.600
filled.

00:05:51.600 --> 00:05:56.720
And second, to get inspiration for what your software should, or maybe shouldn't, do.

00:05:56.720 --> 00:06:01.119
So what's the premier tool out there for 3D visualization currently?

00:06:01.119 --> 00:06:03.040
Blender.

00:06:03.040 --> 00:06:07.859
Blender is a 3D modeling, rendering, sculpting, simulation, visual effects, and everything

00:06:07.859 --> 00:06:12.040
but the Kitchen Sink software package, open source.

00:06:12.040 --> 00:06:17.640
It's an extremely powerful piece of software that produces absolutely breathtaking 3D renderings,

00:06:17.640 --> 00:06:19.880
including 3D data visualizations.

00:06:19.880 --> 00:06:25.279
Here are a few examples taken with permission from artists and cartographers who use Blender

00:06:25.279 --> 00:06:29.320
to visualize data with gorgeous results.

00:06:29.320 --> 00:06:31.079
There's a few issues, however.

00:06:31.119 --> 00:06:37.040
First, Blender is primarily a GUI-based application, as you see here, along with the text I have

00:06:37.040 --> 00:06:38.040
added.

00:06:38.040 --> 00:06:40.799
And GUI-based workflows are not reproducible.

00:06:40.799 --> 00:06:45.079
One of the benefits of using R to power your visualization and analysis pipeline is that

00:06:45.079 --> 00:06:50.119
you can reproduce old analyses years after the fact, rerun the same exact analyses on

00:06:50.119 --> 00:06:54.359
new batches of data, and make slight changes to figures without having to redo the entire

00:06:54.359 --> 00:06:55.679
thing.

00:06:55.679 --> 00:06:59.799
There's a Python interface to Blender, but it's primarily aimed at developers, not at

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:02.000
data scientists and analysts.

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:04.440
Data is not a first-class citizen.

00:07:04.440 --> 00:07:08.480
Additionally, you're here at this conference because you've at least somewhat invested

00:07:08.480 --> 00:07:11.600
yourself in the R ecosystem.

00:07:11.600 --> 00:07:15.679
You've taken workshops, read tutorials, and presumably have spent a good deal of time

00:07:15.679 --> 00:07:22.480
becoming familiar and maybe even an expert in R. And all of those skills will be absolutely

00:07:22.480 --> 00:07:29.480
useless when it comes to learning Blender, except for maybe robust anger management techniques.

00:07:30.480 --> 00:07:36.000
Which, if you saw Jenny Bryan's keynote this morning, you'll know the frustration of seeing

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:40.559
Objective-type closure is not subsettable for the first time.

00:07:40.559 --> 00:07:45.720
So it's a stretch to ask most people to learn one complex piece of software.

00:07:45.720 --> 00:07:50.320
Learning two to perform a single task makes that task inaccessible to all but the most

00:07:50.320 --> 00:07:53.760
perseverant of individuals.

00:07:53.760 --> 00:07:57.399
So for a surface-plotting API, I have a few goals in mind.

00:07:57.399 --> 00:08:02.239
First and foremost, you should never have to think about vertices or triangles or polygons.

00:08:02.239 --> 00:08:06.679
I want a 3D-plotting interface that's focused around data, not computer graphics.

00:08:06.679 --> 00:08:10.519
Secondly, I want to avoid introducing new interfaces you'll have to learn.

00:08:10.519 --> 00:08:14.600
I want to use as much as what you already know to lower the barrier to entry for using

00:08:14.600 --> 00:08:16.920
the software.

00:08:16.920 --> 00:08:20.720
And finally, I want the interface to be friendly and simple enough that people feel like they

00:08:20.720 --> 00:08:22.359
can play with it.

00:08:22.359 --> 00:08:27.640
Because play and experimentation is the fuel for creativity and learning.

00:08:27.640 --> 00:08:29.399
And what fills all these requirements?

00:08:29.399 --> 00:08:30.399
ggplot.

00:08:30.399 --> 00:08:36.039
It's a plotting library that's data-centric, well-known by many people, and easy to experiment

00:08:36.039 --> 00:08:37.119
with.

00:08:37.119 --> 00:08:42.679
So you might be asking, wait, ggplot2 is a 2D-plotting library.

00:08:42.679 --> 00:08:45.400
Is there a ggplot3 I don't know about?

00:08:45.400 --> 00:08:50.599
No, but I'll tell you how you can transform into 3D.

00:08:50.599 --> 00:08:52.400
Recall what I said earlier.

00:08:52.400 --> 00:08:57.679
To plot a 3D surface, all you need are three variables that we map to the X, Y, and Z directions.

00:08:57.679 --> 00:09:02.520
The X and Y aesthetics are built into ggplot, and we encode the third aesthetic representing

00:09:02.520 --> 00:09:04.719
height to color.

00:09:04.719 --> 00:09:10.359
Then we've encoded all three variables of our 3D surface into our ggplot.

00:09:10.359 --> 00:09:14.719
Images are, generally speaking, several matrices just layered together, each which specifies

00:09:14.719 --> 00:09:16.260
a color intensity.

00:09:16.260 --> 00:09:23.219
So even an image can be a height matrix, for better or for worse.

00:09:23.219 --> 00:09:25.979
Sorry, Hadley.

00:09:25.979 --> 00:09:30.400
The plot3D function, which performs all the 3D mapping logic, only cares that it's past

00:09:30.400 --> 00:09:32.580
a matrix of height values in an image.

00:09:32.580 --> 00:09:37.219
If we encode our data into one of those color layers, we can then extract a matrix of height

00:09:37.219 --> 00:09:42.500
values from our ggplot and create a 3D surface onto which we can paint our data.

00:09:42.500 --> 00:09:46.619
By swapping the ggplot's palette to a grayscale black and white palette, it ensures we have

00:09:46.619 --> 00:09:50.460
a one-to-one relationship between our data and our height value.

00:09:50.460 --> 00:09:55.219
We then strip out all the non-color elements and non-data elements, axes, labels, backgrounds,

00:09:55.219 --> 00:09:59.659
text, and our grayscale image now represents a height map of the surface.

00:09:59.659 --> 00:10:07.859
We then drop this into plot3D along with the ggplot texture, and now we have our 3D ggplot.

00:10:07.859 --> 00:10:13.419
You might ask, wait, you guarantee me little to no effort on my part.

00:10:13.419 --> 00:10:18.700
Stripping out all these theme elements seems like a lot of effort, and it is, which is

00:10:18.700 --> 00:10:24.919
why I automated the entire process into a single-function plot gg.

00:10:24.919 --> 00:10:32.900
You just pass in the ggplot object, and it transforms it into a 3D surface, no other

00:10:32.900 --> 00:10:33.900
work required.

00:10:33.900 --> 00:10:39.460
No drawing polygons, no fiddling with complex GUIs, just one simple API to call, drop in

00:10:39.460 --> 00:10:44.020
your ggplot, and watch it grow.

00:10:44.020 --> 00:10:48.619
PlotGG works with both the color and fill aesthetics, and RayShader automatically detects

00:10:48.619 --> 00:10:50.219
which one you used.

00:10:50.219 --> 00:10:58.460
Here I used the color aesthetic in a point geome, which is then projected to 3D.

00:10:58.460 --> 00:11:05.780
If you have a complex plot that uses both, you can specify in PlotGG which one to use.

00:11:05.780 --> 00:11:11.859
So 3D plots are best seen in motion, and RayShader includes several functions that you can use

00:11:11.859 --> 00:11:15.340
to bring your viewers on a tour through your data.

00:11:15.340 --> 00:11:21.859
You can use the render camera and render movie functions to pass a series of camera angles

00:11:21.859 --> 00:11:28.299
to swing around your data set, so you can zoom in, around, and save your movie to a

00:11:28.299 --> 00:11:36.099
file to share online or with a loved one.

00:11:36.099 --> 00:11:39.979
So you can also use render snapshot function to take a picture at the current orientation,

00:11:39.979 --> 00:11:44.140
but if you want the user to focus or the viewer to focus on a certain area, you can use the

00:11:44.140 --> 00:11:49.000
same trick cinematographers use when they want to direct a viewer's attention in a movie.

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:56.719
Use depth of field to pull focus onto the area of interest with the render depth function.

00:11:56.719 --> 00:12:01.359
You can also add titles and image overlays when taking snapshots and rendering movies.

00:12:01.359 --> 00:12:04.679
Here I added a title to describe this plot, which is the classic Public Health London

00:12:04.679 --> 00:12:10.479
cholera data set, here visualizing the number of nearest neighbors at infection sites.

00:12:10.479 --> 00:12:16.159
So I added this legend as an overlay to clearly label the number of nearest neighbors.

00:12:16.159 --> 00:12:18.119
So that's this thing up here.

00:12:18.239 --> 00:12:22.880
I also used the render label function in Ratiator to add a floating text label at the site of

00:12:22.880 --> 00:12:28.320
the water pump where the infection site is being spread from.

00:12:28.320 --> 00:12:32.419
Some might say that it's improper to map the same variable to two separate aesthetics.

00:12:32.419 --> 00:12:35.640
This visualization is showing the number of measles cases in the world reported by the

00:12:35.640 --> 00:12:40.520
WHO mapped to both color and height, which is a redundant mapping.

00:12:40.520 --> 00:12:44.520
But redundancy can be good because it can improve the accessibility and interpretability

00:12:44.520 --> 00:12:45.520
of our plots.

00:12:45.919 --> 00:12:47.840
3D plots have some downside.

00:12:47.840 --> 00:12:49.359
Data can obscure other data behind it.

00:12:49.359 --> 00:12:52.559
The use of perspective can make comparisons between data points harder if there's a lot

00:12:52.559 --> 00:13:01.520
of spatial variation in depth, and the users generally lose the ability to pull out the

00:13:01.520 --> 00:13:04.080
exact values of the z-axis.

00:13:04.080 --> 00:13:09.000
However, it also has some perceptual advantages over color.

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:12.719
Color perception varies from person to person, so what might be an obvious difference between

00:13:12.719 --> 00:13:14.719
one person might not be to another.

00:13:14.719 --> 00:13:18.080
And additionally, how our eyes interpret color is highly nonlinear.

00:13:18.080 --> 00:13:22.559
And even if you pick a good palette like those in the Viridis package, as we have here, readers

00:13:22.559 --> 00:13:26.760
have to understand how to read and reference a color bar, which not all people do.

00:13:26.760 --> 00:13:32.200
3D plots make it easy to spot outliers and make rough relative comparisons between values.

00:13:32.200 --> 00:13:37.840
Using both color and height can get you the best of both worlds.

00:13:37.840 --> 00:13:42.799
And if you have a truly complex visualization where the 3D surface is actually different

00:13:42.919 --> 00:13:46.559
than the data you're showing, RayShader allows you to do that as well.

00:13:46.559 --> 00:13:51.400
This plot is a simulation of a moon disrupting a ring of satellites, visualizing both the

00:13:51.400 --> 00:13:56.520
motion of the particles as well as the shape of the gravitational potential well.

00:13:56.520 --> 00:13:59.719
Showing how the satellites are falling into the potential well is far more illustrative

00:13:59.719 --> 00:14:02.880
than showing both the 2D plots.

00:14:02.880 --> 00:14:06.719
And creating this visualization was straightforward with PlotGG.

00:14:06.719 --> 00:14:13.119
Instead of passing in a single GG plot, we just pass in a list of two GG plots.

00:14:13.119 --> 00:14:17.559
The first is the texture that's painted on the surface, and the second one is used to

00:14:17.559 --> 00:14:20.000
project it to 3D.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:24.280
Here you can see it in action along with the beautiful resulting animation.

00:14:24.280 --> 00:14:27.039
Now, some of you might not be convinced.

00:14:27.039 --> 00:14:31.159
Because while these plots are cool and the API is simple, they don't have the same visual

00:14:31.159 --> 00:14:33.520
impact as the plots produced by Blender.

00:14:33.520 --> 00:14:38.119
And that's true, because Blender has a realistic rendering algorithm called path tracing that

00:14:38.119 --> 00:14:42.159
can produce photorealistic results, because it actually simulates how light travels through

00:14:42.159 --> 00:14:44.280
the scene.

00:14:44.280 --> 00:14:48.960
RayShader relies on the RGL package for rendering, which uses a faster but less visually striking

00:14:48.960 --> 00:14:51.479
method called rasterization.

00:14:51.479 --> 00:14:55.799
In order to get visualizations that look as good as those produced by Blender, I would

00:14:55.799 --> 00:15:01.960
have to write my own path tracer entirely in R from scratch, integrate it into RayShader,

00:15:01.960 --> 00:15:16.640
and then get it on the CRAN, which I did.

00:15:16.640 --> 00:15:21.840
So introducing render high quality, a RayShader function that calls a built-in integrated

00:15:21.840 --> 00:15:26.440
path tracer to render absolutely stunning 3D data visualizations.

00:15:26.440 --> 00:15:28.440
And the API is dead simple.

00:15:28.440 --> 00:15:31.080
It takes your current RayShader view, or just call the function.

00:15:31.080 --> 00:15:35.840
It takes your current RayShader view, transparently exports it to a built-in path tracer, and

00:15:35.840 --> 00:15:38.679
renders it with realistic light transport.

00:15:38.679 --> 00:15:43.840
No complicated GUIs to learn, no long walkthroughs or tutorials to slog through, no need to even

00:15:43.840 --> 00:15:46.080
learn how path tracing works.

00:15:46.080 --> 00:15:54.679
Just create a 3D plot with RayShader, call the function, and see your data in a new light.

00:15:54.679 --> 00:16:00.719
Speaking of light, you have absolutely full control over how the scene is lit.

00:16:00.719 --> 00:16:06.159
You can customize the color, direction, intensity, number of lights, as well as drop in your

00:16:06.159 --> 00:16:08.599
own lights wherever you see fit.

00:16:08.599 --> 00:16:13.320
You gain full artistic control over how your visualization looks.

00:16:13.320 --> 00:16:19.599
Here I've added a wandering 3D light traveling at a figure 8 around Hobart, Tasmania.

00:16:19.599 --> 00:16:23.479
This is all powered by the RayRender package, which I won't get into here because it's an

00:16:23.479 --> 00:16:25.979
entire talk on its own.

00:16:26.059 --> 00:16:34.340
But whether you want to plot a T-Rex or a teapot, bounce the DVD logo exclusively into

00:16:34.340 --> 00:16:44.099
the corner 100% of the time, create your own gold medal for best Pokemon master, or just

00:16:44.099 --> 00:16:51.539
render 30 to 50 feral pigs on their own lonely planet, you can do it with RayRender, all

00:16:51.539 --> 00:16:55.859
entirely within R.

00:16:55.859 --> 00:17:00.219
And you can use RayRender with RayShader to add the freedom to add whatever you want

00:17:00.219 --> 00:17:02.539
to your visualization.

00:17:02.539 --> 00:17:06.260
Render high quality supports adding 3D models to your 3D RayShader data.

00:17:06.260 --> 00:17:10.420
If you want to add a pig to your map, well, I'm not going to stop you, and in fact I encourage

00:17:10.420 --> 00:17:11.920
it.

00:17:11.920 --> 00:17:15.819
While this particular pig was added just for fun, this capability can be used to augment

00:17:15.819 --> 00:17:19.540
and enhance the story your visualization is trying to tell.

00:17:19.540 --> 00:17:25.219
Let me show you how you can combine all of these capabilities all into one awesome example.

00:17:26.219 --> 00:17:30.420
Here, we start with a regular RayShader version of the space-time plot I showed you earlier.

00:17:30.420 --> 00:17:33.699
A nice 3D view, but we can do better.

00:17:33.699 --> 00:17:38.739
We're using RenderSnapshot to capture frames for our movie, but let's switch to RenderHighQuality

00:17:38.739 --> 00:17:40.660
instead.

00:17:40.660 --> 00:17:44.420
That gives us beautiful ray-traced shadows and realistic light transport.

00:17:44.420 --> 00:17:46.319
But let's go one step further.

00:17:46.319 --> 00:17:51.660
We can use RayRender to pass in additional objects into RenderHighQuality, here to drop

00:17:51.660 --> 00:17:56.540
an actual 3D planet, moon, and asteroid belt into the visualization, and we can animate

00:17:56.540 --> 00:17:58.739
it.

00:17:58.739 --> 00:18:05.260
This is all done entirely within R, simulation, plotting, and rendering, so it's entirely

00:18:05.260 --> 00:18:09.020
reproducible.

00:18:09.020 --> 00:18:13.140
So in summary, transform your GG plots into 3D using RayShader.

00:18:13.140 --> 00:18:17.060
Feel free to experiment with PlotGG and see what you come up with, and if you come up

00:18:17.060 --> 00:18:20.579
with something cool, be sure to post it on Twitter with the hashtag RayShader, hashtag

00:18:20.579 --> 00:18:22.339
rstats.

00:18:22.339 --> 00:18:26.979
If you want to impress your peers and show how R is truly the coolest language for 3D

00:18:26.979 --> 00:18:30.819
visualization, take RenderHighQuality for a spin.

00:18:30.819 --> 00:18:35.819
For more information, documentation, and examples, check out RayShader's website at rayshader.com,

00:18:35.819 --> 00:18:39.900
RayRender's website at rayrender.net, my own personal blog with some very in-depth examples

00:18:39.900 --> 00:18:41.680
at tylermw.com.

00:18:41.680 --> 00:18:45.579
Get the code and check out my master class on GitHub, and find me during the rest of

00:18:45.579 --> 00:18:50.619
the day to get a RayShader hex sticker, and check me out on Twitter at tylermorganwall

00:18:50.619 --> 00:18:54.939
for a constant stream of awesome 3D visualizations and updates.

00:18:54.939 --> 00:18:55.939
Thank you both so much.

00:18:55.939 --> 00:18:56.939
Thanks so much, Tyler.

00:18:56.939 --> 00:19:10.579
I think you just covered the most popular question, which is, where can we get the RayShader

00:19:10.579 --> 00:19:13.380
hex sticker?

00:19:13.380 --> 00:19:14.380
Just find me.

00:19:14.380 --> 00:19:18.660
I think we have about 200 left.

00:19:18.660 --> 00:19:23.579
Is spinning the default behavior of the 3D plots, or can we click and drag to explore

00:19:23.579 --> 00:19:25.300
different stationary angles?

00:19:25.300 --> 00:19:27.420
Yes, you can click and drag.

00:19:27.420 --> 00:19:29.780
RGL, you can just click.

00:19:29.780 --> 00:19:34.020
Spinning is just one of the options in RenderMovie, so you can change the camera angle to whatever

00:19:34.020 --> 00:19:37.560
you want.

00:19:37.560 --> 00:19:40.380
Do we need a fancy graphics card?

00:19:40.380 --> 00:19:42.140
No.

00:19:42.140 --> 00:19:43.140
Not at all.

00:19:43.900 --> 00:19:44.900
It should work on whatever computer.

00:19:44.900 --> 00:19:47.900
It doesn't use your GPU at all.

00:19:47.900 --> 00:19:53.540
Is RayShader compatible with Shiny slash Flex Dashboard?

00:19:53.540 --> 00:19:55.339
Okay.

00:19:55.339 --> 00:19:56.780
So there is a way you can use it.

00:19:56.780 --> 00:20:00.859
You can export it currently to a WebGL object, which you can then render in.

00:20:00.859 --> 00:20:03.520
There are some Shiny apps that show this.

00:20:03.520 --> 00:20:07.459
One of the projects I have for the next year is I've already included a GLTF export in

00:20:07.459 --> 00:20:09.119
the dev version I have.

00:20:09.119 --> 00:20:10.739
That I'm going to include as an export.

00:20:10.739 --> 00:20:13.219
That's a web-transmittable format.

00:20:13.219 --> 00:20:14.219
So I'm going to have that.

00:20:14.219 --> 00:20:17.900
And the other issue with Shiny is if you're running it on a server, RayShader currently

00:20:17.900 --> 00:20:23.020
uses RGL, which doesn't support headless operation, so you can't take snapshots.

00:20:23.020 --> 00:20:25.219
But that's something I'm also working on.

00:20:25.219 --> 00:20:28.260
I have some projects working on.

00:20:28.260 --> 00:20:32.459
Can layers be added to RayShader maps, such as roads or structure?

00:20:32.459 --> 00:20:33.459
Yes.

00:20:33.459 --> 00:20:34.699
So there's an add overlay function.

00:20:34.699 --> 00:20:36.099
Watch my talk from last year.

00:20:36.099 --> 00:20:40.219
But yes, there's an add overlay function, and there's a great package called GeoViz,

00:20:40.219 --> 00:20:47.339
which allows you to add floating lines for movement tracks, paragliding tracks, GPS tracks.

00:20:47.339 --> 00:20:50.540
A lot of people have done some very cool stuff with that.

00:20:50.540 --> 00:20:53.739
Does RayShader play well with GGAnimate?

00:20:53.739 --> 00:20:55.260
No.

00:20:55.260 --> 00:20:58.300
That's also a future plot, a future goal.

00:20:58.300 --> 00:20:59.300
Great.

00:20:59.300 --> 00:21:02.979
I'm sure you've never heard this one before.

00:21:02.979 --> 00:21:06.140
RayShader scientists spend a lot of time asking if they could.

00:21:06.140 --> 00:21:09.500
Did they also ask if they should?

00:21:09.500 --> 00:21:10.500
Yes.

00:21:10.500 --> 00:21:16.939
So go to my blog, read my blog post where I talk about 3D GG plots with RayShader.

00:21:16.939 --> 00:21:23.219
And I do talk about some of the thoughts for why I think that 3D can be good.

00:21:23.219 --> 00:21:27.219
I think one of the issues with 3D is really it's more been about the tooling hasn't supported

00:21:27.219 --> 00:21:28.939
it through the years.

00:21:28.939 --> 00:21:31.380
So I think that's a key part that's been missing.

00:21:31.380 --> 00:21:37.339
So when the tooling mostly supports 3D pie charts, you're going to get a lot of bad plots.

00:21:37.339 --> 00:21:41.180
But if the tooling supports something better, then I think that's what I'm trying to do

00:21:41.180 --> 00:21:42.180
at least.

00:21:42.180 --> 00:21:43.180
Great.

00:21:43.180 --> 00:21:44.300
A couple more.

00:21:44.300 --> 00:21:46.780
How long does it take for the movies to render?

00:21:46.780 --> 00:21:51.780
And I'll just add to that, what's the average temperature of your computer?

00:21:51.780 --> 00:21:55.380
So when I'm doing the non-ray traced and path traced ones, they're pretty quick.

00:21:55.380 --> 00:21:59.339
You can get one of those in under a few minutes as long as it's not too large.

00:21:59.339 --> 00:22:04.819
The ray traced ones, well, my computer sits at 100 C the entire for like eight hours straight.

00:22:04.819 --> 00:22:05.819
It's probably not good.

00:22:05.819 --> 00:22:07.260
It's going to kill my computer.

00:22:07.260 --> 00:22:09.060
So yeah, it depends on the quality though.

00:22:09.060 --> 00:22:13.900
You can adjust the number of samples to get a lower quality if you just want to demo something

00:22:13.900 --> 00:22:14.900
out.

00:22:14.900 --> 00:22:20.619
But when you render something with a path tracer, it's like six to eight hours for a 12 second

00:22:20.619 --> 00:22:21.619
video.

00:22:21.619 --> 00:22:24.060
So yes, a long time.

00:22:24.060 --> 00:22:29.900
And then last one is, where can we find good 3D geospatial data to practice with?

00:22:29.900 --> 00:22:35.540
So if you go to my master class, I actually have five data guides that list data for the

00:22:35.540 --> 00:22:39.459
entire world, the US, several cities.

00:22:39.459 --> 00:22:44.260
It gives you instructions on how to extract height data from LiDAR, which includes buildings.

00:22:44.260 --> 00:22:48.939
And I give you very, very detailed instructions on exactly what to click and how to get the

00:22:48.939 --> 00:22:52.339
data so you can easily create whatever map you want.

00:22:52.339 --> 00:22:53.339
Great.

00:22:53.339 --> 00:22:54.900
Well, let's have another round of applause for Tyler.

00:22:54.900 --> 00:22:55.900
Thanks so much.

